: The specific epithet (Latin, noun in apposition) alludes to the conspicuously short tarsi.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="32" pageNumber="95" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="32.[189,794,809,2081]" pageId="32" pageNumber="95">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,319,809,833]" pageId="32" pageNumber="95">Description</emphasis>
: Body length 
<quantity box="[485,614,809,833]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.3" metricValueMax="4.7" metricValueMin="3.9" pageId="32" pageNumber="95" unit="mm" value="4.3" valueMax="4.7" valueMin="3.9">3.9–4.7 mm</quantity>
; length of forebody 
<quantity box="[258,387,841,865]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.95" metricValueMax="2.1" metricValueMin="1.8" pageId="32" pageNumber="95" unit="mm" value="1.95" valueMax="2.1" valueMin="1.8">1.8–2.1 mm</quantity>
. Other measurements: head width: 
<quantity box="[189,344,873,897]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.549999999999999" metricValueMax="5.8" metricValueMin="5.3" pageId="32" pageNumber="95" unit="mm" value="0.5549999999999999" valueMax="0.58" valueMin="0.53">0.53–0.58 mm</quantity>
; length of pronotum: 
<quantity box="[569,724,873,897]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.5" metricValueMax="8.0" metricValueMin="7.0" pageId="32" pageNumber="95" unit="mm" value="0.75" valueMax="0.8" valueMin="0.7">0.70–0.80 mm</quantity>
; width of pronotum: 
<quantity box="[353,507,905,929]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.7" metricValueMax="6.1" metricValueMin="5.3" pageId="32" pageNumber="95" unit="mm" value="0.57" valueMax="0.61" valueMin="0.53">0.53–0.61 mm</quantity>
; elytral length at suture: 
<quantity box="[189,344,937,961]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.4" metricValueMax="4.8" metricValueMin="4.0" pageId="32" pageNumber="95" unit="mm" value="0.44" valueMax="0.48" valueMin="0.4">0.40–0.48 mm</quantity>
; elytral width: 
<quantity box="[510,665,937,961]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.4" metricValueMax="9.0" metricValueMin="7.8" pageId="32" pageNumber="95" unit="mm" value="0.84" valueMax="0.9" valueMin="0.78">0.78–0.90 mm</quantity>
. Coloration (
<figureCitation box="[196,275,969,993]" captionStart="Figs 1–30" captionStartId="9.[151,191,1935,1957]" captionTargetBox="[151,1397,244,1921]" captionTargetId="figure-202@9.[151,1398,234,1933]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Figs 1–30: Antenna (1–19), forebody (20, 23, 26), abdomen (21, 24, 27, 29), antero-lateral portion of abdomen in lateral-dorsal view (22, 25, 28), and abdominal segment VII (30) of Orphnebius triacuminatus (1, 20–22), O. gracilis (2, 23–25), O. protuberatus (3, 26–28), O. pertortus (4, 29–30), O. reticulipennis (5), Zyrastilbus almorensis (6), Pheidologitonetes bursata (7), Rabdotodrusilla vara (8), Amaurodera bicarinata (9), A. gilvicornis (10), A. latisulcata (11), A. brevipes (12), A. migritheca (13), A. longisetosa (14), A. calicitheca (15), Drusilla smetanai (16), D. nepalensis (17), D. lativentris (18), and Witteia tensa (19). Scale bars: 1–29: 1.0 mm; 30: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5742266" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5742266/files/figure.png" pageId="32" pageNumber="95">Figs 12</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[286,315,969,993]" captionStart="Figs 43–57" captionStartId="13.[151,191,2001,2023]" captionTargetBox="[151,1398,232,1963]" captionTargetId="figure-141@13.[151,1398,232,1971]" captionText="Figs 43–57: Amaurodera bicarinata (43–46), A. gilvicornis (47–48), A. latisulcata (49–50), A. brevipes (51), A. migritheca (52–54), A. longisetosa (55–56), and A. calicitheca (57): forebody (43, 47, 49, 51, 52, 55, 57); pronotum in dorsal view (44, 50, 53); pronotum in dorso-lateral view (45, 56); abdomen (46, 48, 54). Scale bars: 43, 46–49, 51–52, 54–55, 57: 1.0 mm; 44–45, 50, 53, 56: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5885053" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5885053/files/figure.png" pageId="32" pageNumber="95">51</figureCitation>
): forebody reddish-brown; abdomen reddish to reddish-brown with segment VI dark-brown; legs yellowish with the profemora and the apical portions of the meso- and metafemora brownish; antennae yellowish; maxillary palpi yellowish-brown with the terminal palpomere pale-yellowish.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="32.[189,794,809,2081]" pageId="32" pageNumber="95">
Head (
<figureCitation box="[261,335,1161,1185]" captionStart="Figs 43–57" captionStartId="13.[151,191,2001,2023]" captionTargetBox="[151,1398,232,1963]" captionTargetId="figure-141@13.[151,1398,232,1971]" captionText="Figs 43–57: Amaurodera bicarinata (43–46), A. gilvicornis (47–48), A. latisulcata (49–50), A. brevipes (51), A. migritheca (52–54), A. longisetosa (55–56), and A. calicitheca (57): forebody (43, 47, 49, 51, 52, 55, 57); pronotum in dorsal view (44, 50, 53); pronotum in dorso-lateral view (45, 56); abdomen (46, 48, 54). Scale bars: 43, 46–49, 51–52, 54–55, 57: 1.0 mm; 44–45, 50, 53, 56: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5885053" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5885053/files/figure.png" pageId="32" pageNumber="95">Fig. 51</figureCitation>
) approximately as long as broad or weakly oblong, broadest across eyes; postero-lateral outline between eyes and posterior constriction strongly convex (abruptly convex at posterior angles) in dorsal view; median dorsal portion not impressed; punctation moderately sparse and very fine; interstices without microreticulation and glossy. Eyes large and convex, nearly as long as distance from posterior margin of eye to posterior constriction. Antenna (
<figureCitation box="[582,656,1417,1441]" captionStart="Figs 1–30" captionStartId="9.[151,191,1935,1957]" captionTargetBox="[151,1397,244,1921]" captionTargetId="figure-202@9.[151,1398,234,1933]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Figs 1–30: Antenna (1–19), forebody (20, 23, 26), abdomen (21, 24, 27, 29), antero-lateral portion of abdomen in lateral-dorsal view (22, 25, 28), and abdominal segment VII (30) of Orphnebius triacuminatus (1, 20–22), O. gracilis (2, 23–25), O. protuberatus (3, 26–28), O. pertortus (4, 29–30), O. reticulipennis (5), Zyrastilbus almorensis (6), Pheidologitonetes bursata (7), Rabdotodrusilla vara (8), Amaurodera bicarinata (9), A. gilvicornis (10), A. latisulcata (11), A. brevipes (12), A. migritheca (13), A. longisetosa (14), A. calicitheca (15), Drusilla smetanai (16), D. nepalensis (17), D. lativentris (18), and Witteia tensa (19). Scale bars: 1–29: 1.0 mm; 30: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5742266" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5742266/files/figure.png" pageId="32" pageNumber="95">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
) moderately long and moderately slender, 2.0– 
<quantity box="[569,650,1449,1473]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.3" pageId="32" pageNumber="95" unit="mm" value="2.3">2.3 mm</quantity>
long; antennomere IX approximately 1.5 times as long as broad and antennomere X weakly oblong.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="32.[189,794,809,2081]" pageId="32" pageNumber="95">
Pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[315,389,1545,1569]" captionStart="Figs 43–57" captionStartId="13.[151,191,2001,2023]" captionTargetBox="[151,1398,232,1963]" captionTargetId="figure-141@13.[151,1398,232,1971]" captionText="Figs 43–57: Amaurodera bicarinata (43–46), A. gilvicornis (47–48), A. latisulcata (49–50), A. brevipes (51), A. migritheca (52–54), A. longisetosa (55–56), and A. calicitheca (57): forebody (43, 47, 49, 51, 52, 55, 57); pronotum in dorsal view (44, 50, 53); pronotum in dorso-lateral view (45, 56); abdomen (46, 48, 54). Scale bars: 43, 46–49, 51–52, 54–55, 57: 1.0 mm; 44–45, 50, 53, 56: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5885053" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5885053/files/figure.png" pageId="32" pageNumber="95">Fig. 51</figureCitation>
) moderately slender, 1.26–1.31 times as long as broad, without sexual dimorphism; dorsal surface, except for the glossy median sulcus, with very dense microgranules and opaque; midline with narrow median sulcus reaching neither anterior nor posterior margins; antero-lateral portions with sparse moderately short setae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="32.[189,794,809,2081]" pageId="32" pageNumber="95">
Elytra (
<figureCitation box="[279,354,1769,1793]" captionStart="Figs 43–57" captionStartId="13.[151,191,2001,2023]" captionTargetBox="[151,1398,232,1963]" captionTargetId="figure-141@13.[151,1398,232,1971]" captionText="Figs 43–57: Amaurodera bicarinata (43–46), A. gilvicornis (47–48), A. latisulcata (49–50), A. brevipes (51), A. migritheca (52–54), A. longisetosa (55–56), and A. calicitheca (57): forebody (43, 47, 49, 51, 52, 55, 57); pronotum in dorsal view (44, 50, 53); pronotum in dorso-lateral view (45, 56); abdomen (46, 48, 54). Scale bars: 43, 46–49, 51–52, 54–55, 57: 1.0 mm; 44–45, 50, 53, 56: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5885053" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5885053/files/figure.png" pageId="32" pageNumber="95">Fig. 51</figureCitation>
) approximately 0.6 times as long as pronotum; punctation fine and moderately dense; microreticulation extremely shallow, practically obsolete, traces visible only at high magnification. Hind wings fully developed. Tarsi remarkably short, metatarsus 
<quantity box="[641,794,1897,1921]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.25" metricValueMax="6.5" metricValueMin="6.0" pageId="32" pageNumber="95" unit="mm" value="0.625" valueMax="0.65" valueMin="0.6">0.60–0.65 mm</quantity>
long and approximately 0.6 times as long as metatibia; metatarsomere I barely as long as the combined length of II and III.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="32.[189,794,809,2081]" lastBlockId="32.[831,1436,233,609]" pageId="32" pageNumber="95">Abdomen narrower than elytra; tergites III–V with moderately deep anterior impressions; tergites III–VII with sparse punctures on disc (especially laterally) and at posterior margin; tergite VIII with sparse setiferous punctation in posterior third; tergites III–V with distinct microreticulation composed of transverse meshes; tergites VI–VII without, or with indistinct traces (especially anteriorly) of microsculpture; posterior margin of tergite VII with palisade fringe; posterior margin of tergite VIII weakly convex and serrate.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="32.[831,1436,233,609]" pageId="32" pageNumber="95">
♂: median lobe of aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[1180,1324,489,513]" captionStart="Figs 124–149" captionStartId="18.[192,232,1972,1994]" captionTargetBox="[193,1433,239,1958]" captionTargetId="figure-137@18.[189,1436,232,1971]" captionText="Figs 124–149:AmauroderaschuelkeifromAssam(124–126),A. gilvicornis(127–128),A. bicarinata(129–132),A. latisulcata (133–135), A. brevipes (136–140), A. migritheca (141–146), A. frondium (147–148), and Zyrastilbus almorensis (149): median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view (124–125, 127–134, 136–139, 141–144); spermatheca (126, 135, 140, 145–148); median portion of pronotum (149). Scale bars: 124–125, 127–134, 136–139, 141–144:0.5 mm; 126, 135, 140, 145, 147–148: 0.2 mm; 146, 149: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5885059" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5885059/files/figure.png" pageId="32" pageNumber="95">Figs 136–139</figureCitation>
) approximately 
<quantity box="[911,993,521,545]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="32" pageNumber="95" unit="mm" value="0.6">0.6 mm</quantity>
long; ventral process weakly curved and very acute apically (lateral view).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="32.[831,1436,233,609]" box="[831,1152,585,609]" pageId="32" pageNumber="95">
♀: spermatheca as in 
<figureCitation box="[1061,1148,585,609]" captionStart="Figs 124–149" captionStartId="18.[192,232,1972,1994]" captionTargetBox="[193,1433,239,1958]" captionTargetId="figure-137@18.[189,1436,232,1971]" captionText="Figs 124–149:AmauroderaschuelkeifromAssam(124–126),A. gilvicornis(127–128),A. bicarinata(129–132),A. latisulcata (133–135), A. brevipes (136–140), A. migritheca (141–146), A. frondium (147–148), and Zyrastilbus almorensis (149): median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view (124–125, 127–134, 136–139, 141–144); spermatheca (126, 135, 140, 145–148); median portion of pronotum (149). Scale bars: 124–125, 127–134, 136–139, 141–144:0.5 mm; 126, 135, 140, 145, 147–148: 0.2 mm; 146, 149: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5885059" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5885059/files/figure.png" pageId="32" pageNumber="95">Fig. 140</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="32.[831,1437,649,1121]" pageId="32" pageNumber="95">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[831,1035,649,673]" pageId="32" pageNumber="95">Comparative notes</emphasis>
: Aside from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="FAUVEL" authorityYear="1905" box="[1167,1298,649,673]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Amaurodera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="32" pageNumber="95" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kraepelini">
<emphasis box="[1167,1298,649,673]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="95">A. kraepelini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="CAMERON" authorityYear="1925" box="[1347,1430,649,673]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Amaurodera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="32" pageNumber="95" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigra">
<emphasis box="[1347,1430,649,673]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="95">A. nigra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, three species have been recorded from 
<collectingRegion box="[1254,1345,681,705]" country="Indonesia" name="Sumatera Utara" pageId="32" pageNumber="95">Sumatra</collectingRegion>
: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="ASSING" authorityYear="2016" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Amaurodera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="32" pageNumber="95" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="varicollis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="95">A. varicollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2016" box="[893,1045,713,737]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Amaurodera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="32" pageNumber="95" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="disparicollis">
<emphasis box="[893,1045,713,737]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="95">A. disparicollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="ASSING" authorityYear="2016" box="[1099,1206,713,737]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Amaurodera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="32" pageNumber="95" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinans">
<emphasis box="[1099,1206,713,737]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="95">A. spinans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2017" box="[1217,1436,713,737]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Amaurodera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="32" pageNumber="95" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevipes">
<emphasis box="[1217,1436,713,737]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="95">Amaurodera brevipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinguished from all of them by smaller body size, a less slender pronotum, shorter and less slender antennae, shorter legs with much shorter tarsi, and by the primary sexual characters, from all the species except 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2016" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Amaurodera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="32" pageNumber="95" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="disparicollis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="95">A. disparicollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also by uniformly yellowish antennae. The similar shapes of the aedeagus and the spermatheca suggest that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2017" box="[831,944,937,961]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Amaurodera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="32" pageNumber="95" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevipes">
<emphasis box="[831,944,937,961]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="95">A. brevipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, too, is closely allied to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="FAUVEL" authorityYear="1905" box="[1244,1374,937,961]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Amaurodera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="32" pageNumber="95" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kraepelini">
<emphasis box="[1244,1374,937,961]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="95">A. kraepelini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The aedeagus of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2017" box="[959,1072,969,993]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Amaurodera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="32" pageNumber="95" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevipes">
<emphasis box="[959,1072,969,993]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="95">A. brevipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, however, is much smaller, and the ventral process is slightly broader (ventral view), apically less acute, and subapically more strongly curved (lateral view). For illustrations of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="FAUVEL" authorityYear="1905" box="[1153,1284,1065,1089]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Amaurodera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="32" pageNumber="95" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kraepelini">
<emphasis box="[1153,1284,1065,1089]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="95">A. kraepelini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="ASSING" authorityYear="2016" box="[1309,1430,1065,1089]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Amaurodera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="32" pageNumber="95" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="varicollis">
<emphasis box="[1309,1430,1065,1089]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="95">A. varicollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2016" box="[831,983,1097,1121]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Amaurodera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="32" pageNumber="95" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="disparicollis">
<emphasis box="[831,983,1097,1121]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="95">A. disparicollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="ASSING" authorityYear="2016" box="[1040,1147,1097,1121]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Amaurodera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="32" pageNumber="95" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinans">
<emphasis box="[1040,1147,1097,1121]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="95">A. spinans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
see 
<bibRefCitation author="ASSING, V." box="[1191,1337,1097,1121]" pageId="32" pageNumber="95" pagination="5 - 20" refId="ref32629" refString="ASSING, V. 2003: A review of the Himalayan species of Amaurodera (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Aleocharinae). - Entomological Problems 33 (1): 5 - 20." type="journal article" year="2003">ASSING (2003</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="ASSING, V." box="[1347,1415,1097,1121]" pageId="32" pageNumber="95" pagination="13 - 111" refId="ref33270" refString="ASSING, V. 2016 b: On some Lomechusini of the Palaearctic and Oriental regions (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Aleocharinae). - Contributions to Entomology 66 (1): 13 - 111 - DOI: 10.21248 / contrib. entomol. 66.1.013 - 111." type="journal article" year="2016">2016b</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
